  "prompt": "Why does shaking a soda cause it to explode?",
  "response": "Shaking a soda can or bottle causes it to explode because it disrupts the gas-liquid equilibrium inside the container. Soda contains dissolved carbon dioxide (CO\u2082) that is kept under pressure. When the container is shaken, the dissolved CO\u2082 forms bubbles that move throughout the liquid. These bubbles adhere to the walls and surface of the container, creating nucleation sites and causing the pressurized gas to come out of the liquid.\n\nAdditionally, the kinetic energy from shaking increases the rate at which CO\u2082 escapes from the liquid into the bubbles. When the container is opened, the pressure inside drops abruptly. The rapid release of pressure allows the bubbles to expand quickly, pushing the liquid out of the container in a frothy explosion.\n\nThe key factors in causing an explosive reaction are the formation of bubbles, increased internal pressure due to these bubbles, and the sudden release of pressure when the container is opened.",
